      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become intertwined in such a way that the state of one particle directly affects the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine you have a pair of magical, entangled gloves, one in your hand and one in a distant land. If you put on the left glove, the other glove will instantly become right, even if it's on the other side of the world. This is similar to how entangled particles behave, but with a twist — they are not just correlated, they are connected in a way that defies classical physics.\n\nNow, let's talk about classical correlation. In the world of classical physics, objects can be correlated without being entangled. For example, if you have two coins that always land on heads when you flip them together, that's a correlation. But if you flip them separately, each coin's outcome is independent of the other. In contrast, with entangled particles, the outcome of one particle's measurement instantly determines the outcome of the other, no matter the distance between them. It's like having a pair of magical, entangled coins that always land on the same side, even if they're on opposite sides of the world. This spooky action at",
