    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the glove thing but it's still a bit confusing. why did Einstein call it 'spooky action at a distance' though? what exactly is so weird about it compared to just normal things being connected?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because he found the idea that two particles could instantly affect each other's state, no matter how far apart they were, to be counterintuitive and at odds with the principles of classical physics. In the classical world, objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings, and information cannot travel faster than the speed of light. Entanglement, however, seems to suggest that there's a hidden, instantaneous connection between particles that defies this limit.\n\nImagine you have two magical, entangled goblins, one in your backyard and the other in a distant forest. If you give the goblin in your backyard a red hat, the goblin in the forest will instantly wear a blue hat, even if it's on the other side of the world. This instant connection between the goblins, regardless of distance, is what Einstein found so \"spooky.\" It's weird because it challenges our understanding of how the universe works, suggesting that there's more to reality than just the physical laws we know.\n\nIn summary, Einstein found entanglement strange because it seemed to violate the fundamental principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light, making it a truly \"spooky\" phenomenon in the realm of physics.",
      "source": "target",
